AGI - The Privacy Guarantor has sanctioned an Asl for 75 thousand euros for not having correctly configured the methods of access to the electronic health dossier (Dse).> The Authority acted as a result of some complaints and reports complaining of the unlawful processing of personal data carried out through the storage and reporting system of the services provided by the health company. In particular, repeated access to the Dse was reported by healthcare personnel not involved in the patient care process. In one case, an Asl professional was in fact able to see the lab exams of the ex-husband unknowed while being the latter not in care of her.
&nbsp;
From the verifications carried out by the Authority it emerged that the management system of the Dse >consentiva to the sanitary operators to manually insert, through self-certification, the reason why it was necessary to access the health dossier. Access to the document was also allowed, by default, to a wide list of professional figures that nothing had to do with the patient care path, including administrative staff: all in violation of the provisions of the Privacy Authority > with the "Guidelines in the matter of Health Dossier" of June 2015, with which the Authority has established that "the controller must pay particular attention to the identification of the authorization profiles, adopting technical methods of authentication to the dossier that confirm the cases of access of each structure" ensuring that access to the dossier is limited to the only health personnel that intervenes over time in the process of care of the patient.
&nbsp;
The Garante has finally ascertained further unlawful, including the failure of an alert system, aimed at identifying abnormal or at-risk behaviors related to the operations carried out by the data processors (e.g. the number of accesses performed, the type or time frame of the same). In addition to applying the administrative sanction, the Authority has therefore ordered the Asl to implement all the technical and organizational measures necessary to ensure the security of the personal data processed and prevent new abusive access.
